{"url": "https://www.reddit.com/r/learnprogramming/comments/9bve3a/how_to_stay_in_the_code_as_an_architect/", "text": "Hey there folks.  I've been in IT for almost 10 years with experience in infrastructure as well as applicatiin development.  I took on an \"architectural\" role about 2 years ago when we moved to scaled agile and I'm starting to feel a bit hands off. Anyone have any advice on keeping up with things when you are pretty hands off day to day? ", "score": 3, "comments": [{"body": "From my experience as an architect I definitely sympathize from being away from the code. While it is temping to jump right in and deal with the most complex parts of the code, writing code is no longer your main function.\n\nWhat I do is try to find small things I can code on. A POC or perhaps a ticket that has been lagging in the queue because of other pressing matters. ", "id": "e566b03", "replies": []}, {"body": "I would ask this in /r/cscareerquestions ", "id": "e568nz2", "replies": [{"body": "Good call!", "id": "e56p6xb", "replies": []}]}, {"body": "Automation is an easy way to stay in code. Find ways to automate the creation of projects, building of projects, deployment of projects, etc. As an architect, you should pretty much have a few one-liners in your bash\\_profile to CRUDeploy your own projects. Presumably, your team has a generic \"kick starter\" for most app development. Make that into a script. See if you can't build similar tools to *Rails* generators. ", "id": "e55ztiv", "replies": []}], "title": "How to stay in the code as an architect"}